2. Explaining the “extra things” in the CMP diagrams
You mentioned FortiManager, HA, subnets, etc. These are all platform plumbing around F5; Gardener doesn’t implement them but must be aware they exist.

Very briefly:

HA (High Availability)

CMP creates F5 in pairs (active/standby).
Internal floating/self IPs and dedicated HA networks let one device take over if the other fails.
This guarantees that both CP‑VIP and app VIPs stay reachable during F5 failures.
Subnets / Networks

CMP chooses:
Management subnet: where BIG‑IP/CCP APIs live (Seed and CIS must reach this).
External subnet(s): where VIPs live, reachable by clients.
Internal/data subnets: where backend servers (Seed / Shoot workers) live.
They also attach security groups/firewall rules allowing:
Seed ↔ CCP API,
F5 ↔ Seed/Shoot networks.
FortiManager / Firewalls

FortiManager (or similar) manages firewall policies around those subnets:
Which VIPs are exposed to Internet,
Which backend networks F5 may reach,
Which ports are allowed.
When CMP provisions a new LB or VS, it also pushes matching firewall rules.
AAA / Licensing / Monitoring (Prometheus)

AAA: internal auth/accounting for F5 usage.
Licensing: ensuring each F5 instance is licensed.
Prometheus: scraping metrics from F5 and LBaaS components.
All of this is Airtel platform responsibility; Gardener just consumes the exposed pieces (API endpoints, VIPs, connectivity).

